{
  "id": "c64ae368-f99a-4d07-926a-eee05798ab94",
  "slug": "litigation-ca-privilege-log-generator",
  "name": "California Privilege Log Generator",
  "summary": "This skill guides an advanced LLM to generate a California-compliant privilege log for withheld or redacted discovery materials under CCP \u00a7 2031.240. It walks through metadata normalization, the drafting of sufficiently specific descriptions to satisfy the Hernandez standard, and the proper application of California Evidence Code sections 952 and 954 (attorney-client privilege) and CCP section 2018.030 (work product doctrine). The workflow emphasizes defensible descriptions that enable assessment without revealing privileged substance, flags waiver risks including third-party disclosure and mixed business/legal communications, and includes mandatory anti-hallucination and attorney-review guardrails.",
  "content": "# California Privilege Log Generator\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill produces a California-compliant privilege log for documents withheld or redacted in discovery on the basis of attorney-client privilege, work product protection, and closely related California confidentiality doctrines. In California civil practice, the privilege log is not a clerical afterthought; it is a strategic and compliance-critical work product that frequently determines whether privileged material remains protected or is ordered produced. A poorly prepared log\u2014one characterized by boilerplate descriptions, missing metadata, or incomplete participant identification\u2014can trigger waiver arguments, motions to compel, in camera review, cost-shifting sanctions, or court-ordered disclosure of sensitive attorney communications and attorney mental impressions.\n\nGood execution requires a delicate balance: providing sufficient factual information to allow the requesting party and the court to evaluate the privilege claim, while simultaneously avoiding the disclosure of the very confidential information the privilege is intended to protect. The log must align with California's statutory privilege framework (not federal common law), reflect the applicable discovery statutes governing motions to compel and protective orders, and anticipate the adversarial use of the log by opposing counsel. This skill guides an advanced LLM through that workflow with the level of care expected of competent California litigation counsel, subject to mandatory attorney supervision and verification.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nA privilege log exists because California's discovery regime generally requires parties to respond meaningfully to inspection demands and other discovery requests while preserving legitimate protections. Under Code of Civil Procedure section 2031.240(c)(1), if a party objects to a demand for inspection based on privilege, it must provide sufficient factual information for the other party to evaluate the merits of the claim. The log is therefore both a compliance artifact and a litigation positioning document: it signals the reasonableness of your privilege assertions, frames the dispute for the meet-and-confer record, and often becomes an exhibit to discovery motions.\n\nIn California state court, privilege claims are governed primarily by the Evidence Code (attorney-client privilege, Cal. Evid. Code \u00a7 950 et seq.) and the Code of Civil Procedure (work product doctrine, CCP \u00a7 2018.010 et seq.). Attorney-client privilege is codified at Evidence Code section 954, with key definitional provisions including section 952's definition of \"confidential communication between client and lawyer.\" Work product protection is codified at Code of Civil Procedure section 2018.030, which distinguishes between absolute protection for writings reflecting an attorney's impressions, conclusions, opinions, or legal research and theories, and qualified protection for other attorney work product that may be overcome only upon a showing of denial that would unfairly prejudice the party or result in injustice.\n\nThe primary audiences for a privilege log are opposing counsel evaluating whether to accept or challenge your privilege claims, the court if a discovery dispute is presented, and your own client and trial team because the log becomes part of the record of what exists and what is being protected. Opposing counsel's expectations are practical: entries should be consistent, non-evasive, and sufficiently specific to assess privilege. Judges' expectations are similarly pragmatic: they want clarity, internal consistency, and a log that can be used efficiently for sampling or in camera review when justified.\n\nThe California standard for log sufficiency, as clarified in Hernandez v. Superior Court (2003) 112 Cal.App.4th 285, requires identification of the document type, date, author, recipients, and the specific ground for withholding. If the log fails to provide this foundation, the court may find the objecting party has failed to meet its burden of proof, potentially leading to in camera review or an order to produce. The party asserting the privilege bears the initial burden of proving that the communication was made in the course of an attorney-client relationship (Wellpoint Health Networks, Inc. v. Superior Court (1997) 59 Cal.App.4th 110).\n\nStrategically, the log should accomplish three things simultaneously. First, it should preserve the privilege by avoiding over-description that discloses substance. Second, it should deter challenges by clearly tying the document's participants and purpose to the statutory elements. Third, it should create a defensible record showing diligence and good faith in response\u2014important because California discovery disputes turn heavily on meet-and-confer efforts and proportional remedies.\n\nScope boundary: this skill focuses on generating the privilege log itself, including California-tailored privilege descriptions and metadata handling. It does not draft the underlying discovery responses, meet-and-confer letters, motions to compel or protective orders, or declarations supporting privilege claims, although it will flag when those may be needed.\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore generating entries, the LLM must have enough information to accurately describe each withheld or redacted document without revealing privileged substance, and to connect the claim to California's statutory elements. At minimum, the LLM should obtain the following inputs.\n\nThe discovery requests at issue are essential context, including the RFP set number, request text, and any applicable definitions and instructions, because the log often references which request prompted withholding. The party's responses and any agreed-upon ESI protocol or logging format should be reviewed because they may dictate specific column headings, metadata fields, or categorical logging approaches.\n\nThe population of withheld and redacted documents must be provided, either as a full set or a representative sample if the court or parties agreed to categorical logging. This should include Bates ranges if applicable. For each document, the LLM needs available metadata: date, author, recipients including CC and BCC, subject line or file name, document type, attachment status, custodians, and where it was found.\n\nA party and counsel roles list is indispensable. This should identify key individuals and their roles\u2014for example, \"Jane Doe, General Counsel for Defendant,\" \"John Smith, Outside Litigation Counsel at [Firm],\" \"Robert Roe, VP of Operations for Defendant.\" Without this, the LLM cannot determine whether a communication was between a client and lawyer or involved a potentially privilege-destroying third party.\n\nThe privilege basis for each document should be specified: attorney-client privilege, work product (absolute or qualified), joint defense or common interest, attorney-client with agents, or a combination. The matter timeline is vital for work product claims, indicating when litigation was anticipated or commenced. Any privilege waiver risks should be identified, such as third-party dissemination, forwarding chains, or mixed business and legal advice. Finally, any protective order, confidentiality stipulation, or clawback agreement relevant to in camera review should be noted.\n\nThe LLM should ask targeted follow-up questions when information is missing. For example: Who is the client representative? Are the listed participants employees, former employees, outside consultants, or third parties? If consultants are involved, what was their role\u2014for example, interpreter, e-discovery vendor, or accountant engaged to assist counsel? Was litigation anticipated at the time the document was created? Are there attachments, and are they separately logged? Are redactions partial, requiring both production and logging?\n\nIf any required metadata or privilege basis is unavailable, the LLM must pause and ask for the missing inputs rather than guessing. The highest-risk failure mode is inventing author and recipient roles or legal bases that are not supported by the record.\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Process\n\n### Step 1: Confirm the Governing Forum, Discovery Posture, and Logging Standard\n\nBegin by anchoring the privilege log to the correct procedural and legal context. California state court privilege analysis is statutory; while federal case law may be persuasive on some discovery-management issues, California Evidence Code and CCP provisions control privilege and work product. Confirm whether the matter is in California Superior Court civil litigation governed by the Civil Discovery Act, a special proceeding with modified discovery rules, or a California action removed to federal court, which changes privilege-log expectations even if state privilege law may apply to state-law claims under Erie.\n\nThen confirm what the parties and the court expect by way of logging. In California practice, privilege logs are frequently exchanged by agreement or court order, and Hernandez v. Superior Court (2003) 112 Cal.App.4th 285 explicitly rejected the idea that a privilege log is not required until a motion to compel is filed. The log should be served with or very shortly after discovery responses to avoid waiver arguments. If there is an ESI protocol, case management order, or stipulation defining the format, follow it. If not, use a conventional, litigation-defensible format containing the metadata columns necessary to evaluate the claim without revealing substance.\n\nDecide early whether the log will be document-by-document, categorical, or hybrid. Categorical logs can reduce burden in large cases but increase challenge risk if categories are overbroad or do not map to privilege elements. If categorical logging is contemplated, confirm that opposing counsel agrees or that a court order permits it; otherwise, generate document-level entries.\n\nCommon mistakes include blindly copying a federal-style log format without considering California's statutory language, or producing a skeletal log that omits roles and relationships and invites a motion to compel. Adversarially, opposing counsel will use ambiguity against you, asserting that you have not met your burden to support the claim and requesting in camera review or waiver.\n\n### Step 2: Build a Defensible Document Inventory and Normalize Metadata\n\nPrivilege logs fail most often because the underlying inventory is inaccurate. The LLM should first create or ingest a structured dataset for withheld and redacted items. Each record should have a stable identifier such as a Bates number or unique document ID, and the LLM should preserve document families\u2014email plus attachments and parent-child relationships in ESI. Treat attachments as separate documents for logging purposes unless the parties agreed otherwise, because an attachment may not share the same privilege basis as the parent email.\n\nNormalize dates including time zone if relevant, names with consistent formatting across entries, and roles. A person should not appear as \"J. Smith\" in one entry and \"John Smith\" in another unless verified. For recipients, capture TO, CC, and BCC where available. BCC recipients can create waiver or third-party dissemination issues and should be logged carefully. If an email was CC'd to a third-party vendor without a common interest agreement, the privilege is likely waived, and this must be flagged for attorney review immediately.\n\nWhere the dataset contains subject lines or file names, treat them as potentially privileged. Do not reproduce a subject line that reveals legal advice, litigation strategy, or attorney mental impressions. Instead, translate it into a neutral description such as \"Email regarding request for legal advice\" or \"Draft correspondence for attorney review.\" If the subject line is innocuous, it can be used.\n\nCommon mistakes include logging an email chain as a single document when the chain includes non-privileged segments, failing to log produced-but-redacted documents, or using an internal file path or name that discloses legal strategy. Opposing counsel will scrutinize inconsistencies in date ordering, participant naming, and family relationships to argue the log is unreliable.\n\nAs an illustrative example of safe normalization: if the metadata shows an author \"Outside Counsel\" at a law firm email and recipients including the client CEO and a PR consultant, the log must reflect the PR consultant's role and whether they were necessary to facilitate legal advice. If the PR consultant was not reasonably necessary for transmission or accomplishment of the purpose of the consultation, their presence may defeat confidentiality under Evidence Code section 952.\n\n### Step 3: Determine the Correct Privilege or Protection Basis Under California Law\n\nFor each record, the LLM should classify the privilege or protection basis using California statutory definitions. These are distinct legal doctrines with different elements.\n\nAttorney-client privilege protects confidential communications between client and lawyer made for the purpose of legal consultation (Evid. Code \u00a7\u00a7 952, 954). The privilege is absolute absent waiver, but the party asserting it must establish each element: an attorney-client relationship, a communication made in confidence, and a purpose of seeking or providing legal advice. Focus on whether the participants are the client and lawyer or their authorized representatives, whether confidentiality was maintained with no unnecessary third parties, and whether the purpose was seeking or providing legal advice as distinguished from business advice.\n\nWork product protection applies to writings prepared by or for an attorney in preparation for litigation or in the course of representing a client (CCP \u00a7 2018.030). Absolute protection covers writings reflecting attorney impressions, conclusions, opinions, legal research, or theories (CCP \u00a7 2018.030(a)). Qualified protection covers other attorney work product, which may be discovered only if denial would unfairly prejudice the party or result in injustice (CCP \u00a7 2018.030(b)). Unlike federal law, California's work product doctrine is codified by statute and, in its traditional formulation, belongs to the attorney rather than the client, although in practice the client can often assert it.\n\nIf a document plausibly falls under both attorney-client privilege and work product protection, it is common to assert both. However, do not over-assert reflexively. Over-assertion can undermine credibility and invite broader challenges. The LLM should flag entries where privilege is questionable, such as business advice from a lawyer, communications widely copied to non-legal personnel, or documents created in the ordinary course of business before litigation was anticipated.\n\nAdversarial awareness is critical here. Opposing counsel will attack mixed business and legal communications by invoking the \"dominant purpose\" test articulated in Costco Wholesale Corp. v. Superior Court (2009) 47 Cal.4th 725, arguing that the primary purpose was business rather than legal. They will also challenge communications including third parties, question attorney involvement as a pretext for privilege shielding, and dispute timing for work product claims. The LLM should provide enough context to show the nexus\u2014for example, \"prepared at counsel's direction in connection with threatened litigation regarding [topic]\"\u2014without revealing strategy.\n\n### Step 4: Draft Privilege Log Descriptions Meeting the \"Sufficiently Specific\" Standard\n\nThe description is the heart of the log and the most frequent point of failure. California law requires more than a category; it requires a functional description. The LLM should draft a description that allows the requester to evaluate the privilege claim without disclosing the privileged substance. This means describing the document type and general purpose rather than quoting content.\n\nAvoid boilerplate phrases like \"legal advice\" or \"attorney-client communication.\" These are conclusions, not descriptions. A strong description typically includes the document type (email, letter, memo, draft pleading, investigation notes), the general subject matter framed at a high level, the relationship of the participants identified by role, and the legal purpose such as request for or provision of legal advice or preparation for litigation. When the basis is work product, specify whether it is attorney impressions and opinions subject to absolute protection or other work product subject to qualified protection, and use the statutory language where appropriate.\n\nThe following illustrative examples demonstrate the spectrum from weak to strong execution. A weak description reads: \"Email regarding lawsuit.\" A strong description reads: \"Confidential email thread between VP of Sales and Outside Counsel requesting legal analysis of potential liability under the Supply Agreement following the January 2023 breach notice; withheld under attorney-client privilege (Evid. Code \u00a7\u00a7 952, 954).\" A work product example reads: \"Internal memorandum prepared by litigation counsel summarizing witness interviews and reflecting counsel's mental impressions and legal theories regarding contract interpretation in anticipation of litigation; withheld as attorney work product\u2014absolute (CCP \u00a7 2018.030(a)).\"\n\nFor redacted documents, the description should make clear that a non-privileged version is being produced with privileged portions redacted, and it should identify the redaction basis. California law prefers that you produce a document with redactions rather than withholding it entirely when only a portion is privileged. The log should reflect \"Redacted\" rather than \"Withheld\" in such cases.\n\nCommon mistakes include descriptions so vague they look like bad faith, descriptions so detailed they reveal privileged substance or legal theories, and inconsistent phrasing that implies some documents are less privileged than others. Another frequent error is failing to specify the role of recipients, especially where names are ambiguous. Courts and opposing counsel will not assume \"Alex Lee\" is in-house counsel.\n\n### Step 5: Apply California-Specific Privilege Framing and Mitigate Waiver Risks\n\nCalifornia's attorney-client privilege hinges on \"confidential communication between client and lawyer\" as defined in Evidence Code section 952. That definition requires that communications be transmitted in confidence and not disclosed to third persons other than those present to further the interest of the client in the consultation or those to whom disclosure is reasonably necessary for the transmission of the information or accomplishment of the purpose. Under Evidence Code section 912, the privilege is waived if any holder of the privilege has disclosed a significant part of the communication to a third party. The LLM must incorporate confidentiality-preserving facts into the log where needed, especially where the recipient list includes non-lawyers.\n\nWhen communications include employees, the log should identify them as client representatives with their title and frame the purpose as legal advice to the organizational client. When communications include third parties, the LLM must not assume privilege applies. Instead, it should flag the entry and ask whether the third party was necessary for transmission or to accomplish the purpose of the consultation within the meaning of section 952, whether there is a common-interest or joint-defense arrangement supported by a written agreement, and whether the supervising attorney has confirmed the privilege basis. If uncertain, the entry must be flagged for attorney review rather than logged with an unsupported privilege claim.\n\nFor work product, use the statutory distinction consistently: absolute protection for writings reflecting attorney impressions, conclusions, opinions, or legal research and theories under CCP \u00a7 2018.030(a), and qualified protection for other work product under CCP \u00a7 2018.030(b). If a document involves an expert who has been designated to testify, the work product protection is typically waived upon designation, and this should be flagged.\n\nIllustrative examples of effective California-specific framing include: \"Email from client operations manager to in-house counsel providing factual information requested by counsel for purposes of rendering legal advice; withheld as confidential attorney-client communication (Evid. Code \u00a7\u00a7 952, 954).\" Another example: \"Memorandum prepared by outside counsel summarizing witness interview and reflecting counsel's mental impressions and legal theories in anticipation of litigation; withheld as attorney work product\u2014absolute (CCP \u00a7 2018.030(a)).\"\n\nCommon mistakes include logging entries that implicitly concede non-confidentiality by noting \"copied vendor\" without explaining the vendor's role, or entries that state the business purpose without tying the communication to legal advice. Opposing counsel will use those entries to argue the dominant purpose was business, not legal.\n\n### Step 6: Assemble the Log in Production-Ready Format with Internal Consistency\n\nOnce entries are drafted, assemble the log into a consistent table structure suitable for service. The standard columns for a California privilege log are: Log Entry Number or Bates/Doc ID, Date, Document Type, Author (Name and Role), Recipients To (Name and Role), CC/BCC (Name and Role), Description of Nature and Subject, Privilege Basis (ACP, WPD-Absolute, WPD-Qualified), Legal Authority, and Notes (e.g., Redacted/Produced in part, responsive to RFP No. X). If the parties have agreed to additional fields such as custodian, request number, or attachment relationship, include them.\n\nApply consistent naming conventions, consistent privilege labels (\"Attorney-Client Privilege (Evid. Code \u00a7\u00a7 952, 954)\"; \"Work Product\u2014Absolute (CCP \u00a7 2018.030(a))\"; \"Work Product\u2014Qualified (CCP \u00a7 2018.030(b))\"), and consistent description style. Consistency is not cosmetic: it demonstrates principled privilege analysis rather than ad hoc withholding.\n\nFor email threads, decide whether to log each message individually or the thread as a whole depending on how it will be produced. If a thread contains both privileged and non-privileged segments, counsel often produces non-privileged segments with redactions; the log must reflect that accurately. If a document is undated, state \"Undated\" and provide an estimated date range based on surrounding documents in the thread.\n\nCommon mistakes include mismatching Bates ranges, omitting attachments, listing recipients in a way that hides third parties, or mixing produced and withheld documents without clarifying status. Opposing counsel will reconcile your log against your production load file; discrepancies become credibility problems.\n\n### Step 7: Quality Control, Attorney-Review Flags, and Dispute-Ready Annotations\n\nBefore finalizing, review the log as if you are opposing counsel preparing a motion to compel. Apply a structured quality-control framework to each entry. First, the specificity test: does the description identify a specific legal issue or request for advice, or is it a generic phrase? Second, the identity check: are all authors and recipients identified by name and role, and are there any unidentified names? Third, privilege logic: if work product is claimed, was the document created in anticipation of litigation, and does the date align with the matter timeline? Fourth, the authority check: are Evidence Code sections 952 and 954 and CCP section 2018.030 cited correctly for the asserted basis? Fifth, thread integrity: for email threads, does the log describe the entire thread or just the top-level email, and is the approach consistent?\n\nThe LLM should identify high-risk entries and append internal notes for attorney use that are not for production unless instructed. Examples of appropriate flags include: \"Third-party recipient\u2014confirm necessity under Evid. Code \u00a7 952,\" \"Forwarded to non-legal distribution list\u2014evaluate waiver under Evid. Code \u00a7 912,\" \"Timing pre-litigation\u2014confirm work product basis and triggering events,\" and \"Business/legal mixed\u2014confirm dominant purpose under Costco Wholesale Corp. analysis and assess segregability.\"\n\nIf the client anticipates a motion to compel, it may be useful to create a parallel internal \"defense log\" that includes additional substantiation facts for use in declarations. This companion document must be clearly labeled as attorney work product and not served. The LLM can generate this if requested.\n\nSubstantive accuracy requires that every factual assertion in the log is supported by metadata or verified information from the client team. If the log states \"prepared at counsel's direction,\" confirm that is true. If it states \"litigation anticipated,\" confirm the timeline and triggering events. If any entry's privilege basis is uncertain, the log should either be revised to a defensible basis or flagged for attorney decision. No description should inadvertently disclose legal advice by quoting a subject line that references settlement range or liability assessment.\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\nPrivilege logging implicates core professional responsibility duties because it concerns confidentiality, candor, and competent representation. The LLM must operate with explicit ethical guardrails and require attorney oversight at every stage.\n\nUnder the California Rules of Professional Conduct, Rule 1.1 requires competence, meaning counsel must investigate enough to assert privilege in good faith and avoid waiver through careless logging. Rule 1.6 requires that the log not reveal client confidential information beyond what is legally required, even when some disclosure is necessary to support the privilege claim. Rule 3.3 imposes a duty of candor toward the tribunal: misrepresenting the contents of a document in a privilege log to shield it from discovery is a violation that can lead to sanctions. These California rules, while not identical to the ABA Model Rules, serve parallel functions and should be reviewed in their current form for any case-specific application.\n\nThe party asserting the privilege bears the burden of proof. Under the standard articulated in Wellpoint Health Networks, Inc. v. Superior Court (1997) 59 Cal.App.4th 110, if the log is too vague to establish the foundational elements of the privilege, the objecting party has failed its burden and the court may order production or in camera review.\n\nEvidence Code section 912 provides that the privilege is waived if any holder of the privilege has disclosed a significant part of the communication to a third party. The LLM must flag any entry where third-party disclosure appears in the metadata and require attorney determination of whether a statutory exception applies. For work product, mislabeling a document as \"absolute\" under CCP section 2018.030(a) when it is factual compilation subject only to qualified protection under section 2018.030(b) creates credibility issues and may prompt closer judicial scrutiny of the entire log.\n\nConflicts may arise where communications involve multiple entities, joint representation, common-interest arrangements, or insurer-appointed counsel. The LLM should flag such entries so the supervising attorney can assess conflict and waiver implications under the specific factual circumstances.\n\nAnti-hallucination guardrails are mandatory. The LLM must not invent case citations, statutory provisions, or rules of professional conduct. All statutory citations should be verified against official sources, and any case law reference must be confirmed through web search before inclusion. If a citation cannot be verified, it must be flagged for attorney research rather than presented as authoritative. When executing this skill, the LLM should use search tools to verify any legal citation it generates that is not drawn directly from the skill text.\n\n## 6. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nThis skill is calibrated to California Superior Court practice under the Evidence Code and the Civil Discovery Act. If the matter is in federal court, privilege log practice is commonly driven by Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 26(b)(5)(A), which requires a party withholding information on privilege grounds to expressly make the claim and describe the nature of the documents in a manner that enables assessment without revealing privileged information. Federal courts may also have local rules, standing orders, or judge-specific requirements governing categorical logs, metadata fields, and timing. When practicing in federal court in California, consult the local rules of the specific district, as the Central District, Northern District, Eastern District, and Southern District each have distinct discovery expectations.\n\nIf the matter is a hybrid\u2014for example, federal court applying California privilege law to state-law claims\u2014the privilege elements may remain California statutory, but the logging mechanics and sanctions framework may follow federal procedure. In that scenario, maintain California privilege framing using Evidence Code sections 952 and 954 and CCP section 2018.030 for the substantive basis, but adapt the log structure and timing to the federal judge's requirements.\n\nWithin California, practice varies by case type and department. Complex litigation departments may issue detailed ESI and privilege logging requirements; some judges prefer categorical logs for large productions. Treat any case management order, ESI protocol, or stipulation as controlling and adapt the output accordingly. When such an order exists, implement the specific required fields and deadlines and flag any tension between the order and the default log structure.\n\n## 7. Output Expectations When Executing This Skill\n\nWhen the user provides document metadata, the LLM should produce three deliverables. First, a clean, production-ready privilege log in table form using the agreed or standard column headings, formatted for CSV or Excel export. Second, California-tailored privilege basis language citing Evidence Code sections 952 and 954 and CCP section 2018.030 as applicable to each entry. Third, a separate internal \"attorney review flags\" section listing entries that present waiver risk, uncertain privilege basis, or other substantiation concerns, clearly separated from the served log.\n\nAll outputs require review and approval by a licensed California attorney before service. This skill does not constitute legal advice and must be tailored to local court practices, case management orders, and negotiated ESI protocols as applicable to the specific matter.",
